  "prompt": "Are there statutes that address money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are statutes that address money laundering at both the national and international levels. In the United States, the primary federal statutes that criminalize money laundering are:\n\n1. **The Bank Secrecy Act (BSA) of 1970**: This act requires financial institutions to assist U.S. government agencies in detecting and preventing money laundering. It mandates record-keeping and reporting of certain transactions, such as cash transactions over $10,000, and the reporting of suspicious activities that might signify money laundering, tax evasion, or other criminal activities.\n\n2. **The Money Laundering Control Act of 1986**: This act made money laundering a federal crime. It prohibits individuals from engaging in financial transactions with the proceeds of specified unlawful activities with the intent to promote the carrying on of specified unlawful activity, to engage in tax evasion or fraud, or to conceal the nature, location, source, ownership, or control of the proceeds of specified unlawful activity.\n\n3. **The USA PATRIOT Act of 2001**: This act expanded the scope of the BSA by adding provisions to prevent, detect, and prosecute international money laundering and the financing of terrorism. It also requires financial institutions to implement anti-money laundering (AML) programs and to perform due diligence on correspondent accounts.\n\n4. **The Anti-Drug Abuse Act of 1988**: This act expanded the BSA to include reporting requirements for currency and monetary instrument transportation.\n\nInternationally, there are also agreements and conventions aimed at combating money laundering, such as:\n\n- **The Financial Action Task Force (FATF)**: An intergovernmental organization founded in 1989 on the initiative of the G7 to develop policies to combat money laundering. In 2001, its mandate expanded to include terrorism financing.\n\n- **The United Nations Convention against Illicit Traffic in Narcotic Drugs and Psychotropic Substances (1988)**, also known as the Vienna Convention, was the first international legal instrument to address the issue of money laundering.\n\n- **The United Nations Convention against Transnational Organized Crime (2000)**, also known as the Palermo Convention, includes provisions to combat money laundering related to organized crime.\n\nMany countries have their own laws and regulations that align with these international standards and conventions to prevent and prosecute money laundering activities. These laws typically require financial institutions to monitor customer transactions, report suspicious activities, and maintain records that can be used by law enforcement agencies to trace illicit funds.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
